think The lens: Nock stood in for a permanent portable substrate that did not exist in hardware a decade ago; RISC-V's frozen open base ISA is that substrate now, so Glow targets RISC-V directly where Hoon needed Nock.
think Two backends follow: primary Glow->Zig 0.16.0->RISC-V (already standing, M0-proven arch-portable), and Nock as a second backend for Urbit interop only. The bridge direction is Glow emits Nock, never RISC-V down to Nock.
think The honest trade: Nock gave determinism for free at the VM; targeting RISC-V, Glow re-earns determinism by discipline (TAME bounds, deterministic folds, fold-over-signed-log). This resolves the old fusion fork toward option 3 with a real reason.
think Evaluated recent decisions: Neth/Sala/Pool green folds validate disciplinary determinism on native+aarch64; Aurora/runtime boots onto RISC-V not a Nock VM; the held T-vane is less fraught since determinism is not VM-level here; Glowphone/mikroPhone RISC-V MCU is the substrate; SLC honesty unchanged.
think Preferred silo home: active-reviving, because the core is a reviving decision -- what Glow carries from Hoon (runes, referential transparency) versus changes (target). The reviving index already tracked Glow itself under Rye+Hoon.
